    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Towers or other elevated buildings located at large and medium-sized airports and from which the movement of aircraft and other surrounding traffic is controlled by radio or other means. The control tower structures generally rise high above other buildings at an airport and have windows, tilted outward to avoid glare, circling the entire top floor to allow a clear view for air traffic controllers. They contain necessary equipment, such as radios, radar displays, computer systems for meteorological information and flight data, controllers' headsets, telephone systems, light guns for communication with aircraft via aviation light signals, and wind and pressure gauges.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000114707/Oxford English Dictionary Online (2002-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000093795/Encyclopedia Britannica Online (2002-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Turm oder anders erhöhtes Bauwerk auf einem großen oder mittelgroßen Flughafen, von wo aus die Bewegungen der Flugzeuge und anderer umgebender Verkehr durch Funk oder andere Mittel überwacht wird. Der Kontrollturm ragt gewöhnlich weit über die Flughafengebäude hinaus und sein Obergeschoss hat, um blendendes Licht zu vermeiden, nach außen geneigte Fenster, die den Fluglotsen freie Sicht ermöglichen. Er umfasst notwendige Ausrüstungsgegenstände, wie zum Beispiel Funk, Radarschirme, Computersysteme für meteorologische Informationen und Flugdaten, Controller-Headsets, Telefonsysteme, Signalscheinwerfer für die Kommunikation mit Flugzeugen über Luftverkehrslichtsignale, und Wind- und Luftdruckmessgeräte.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>German</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000232/IfM-SMB-PK</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000122134/IfM Berlin</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Torres ou outros edifícios elevados localizados em aeroportos de grande e médio porte e a partir dos quais o movimento de aeronaves e outros tráfegos circundantes são controlados por rádio ou outros meios. As estruturas da torre de controle geralmente se elevam acima de outros edifícios em um aeroporto e têm janelas inclinadas para fora para evitar ofuscamento, circulando todo o andar superior para permitir uma visão clara dos controladores de tráfego aéreo. Eles contêm equipamentos necessários, como rádios, displays de radar, sistemas de computador para informações meteorológicas e dados de voo, fones de ouvido dos controladores, sistemas telefônicos, pistolas leves para comunicação com aeronaves por meio de sinais luminosos de aviação e medidores de vento e pressão</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Portuguese</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000316/CVAA-BR</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000109633/CVAA-BR Consortium (2020-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
    </Descriptive_Notes>
